1 Who are Gypsies and Travellers?
The term ‘Gypsies and Travellers’ encompasses a range of ethnic and cultural
groups, many of which practice nomadism (where people do not have a single
fixed accommodation but move from place to place) and/or have a nomadic
heritage. Some of the groups included in this label are Welsh Gypsies, Scottish
Gypsy/Travellers and Irish Travellers.4 For further information about Gypsies
and Travellers, see the Library series on Gypsies and Travellers.
A report by the House of Commons Women and Equalities Select Committee
highlights that “while some find the term “Gypsy” to be offensive, many [...]
were proud to associate themselves with this term”. It is therefore also used in
this briefing.5
The government’s planning policy says Gypsies and Travellers are “persons of
nomadic habit of life whatever their race or origin”. The government uses the
term ‘Travellers’ to refer to Gypsies and Travellers.6Gypsies and Travellers: Planning provisions in England

1.1 Assessing and meeting the needs of Gypsies
and Travellers
There are no nationally set targets for the number of Gypsy and Traveller sites
that an LPA must provide. Instead, LPAs should assess and meet the needs of
Gypsies and Travellers in their area in line with the government’s planning
policy for Traveller sites.7
The policy says that LPAs should assess the accommodation needs of Gypsies
and Travellers in their local area, including the needs for both permanent and
temporary accommodation. It advises LPAs to engage with Gypsies and
Travellers as part of this assessment as well as their representative bodies
and local support groups.
Where LPAs identify a need for Gypsy and Traveller sites in their local area,
they should set pitch targets (which are targets for the number and size of
Gypsy and Traveller sites) in their local plans. Their local plans must also
identify land that can provide five years’ worth of accommodation. If an LPA
cannot demonstrate an up-to-date supply of sites to deliver five years’ worth
of accommodation but did identify a local need, the government says that it
should consider granting planning permission to proposed sites unless they
are located in the green belt or protected in another way.8
The policy says that an LPA is not required to meet its need for Gypsy and
Traveller sites in full in “exceptional cases” if an LPA is “burdened by a largescale unauthorised site” and its area is “subject to strict and special planning
constraints”.9
Where LPAs do not identify a need for Gypsy and Traveller sites in their local
area, the policy advises LPAs to nevertheless set out “criteria-based policies”
in their local plan. These policies can then form the basis of decision-making
if there are planning applications for Gypsy and Traveller sites in the future.
