2 What is the role of local plans?
A local plan sets out the LPA’s vision and framework for the development and
land use in their area. It identifies what development is needed, where it
should go and what land is protected. All planning applications are decided
through evaluation against the local plan.11
A local plan must be prepared in line with the government’s National Planning
Policy Framework and its planning policy for Traveller sites.
Before it can be adopted, a local plan must first be examined by the Planning
Inspectorate, an executive agency of Department of Levelling Up, Housing
and Communities. A planning inspector will assess whether the local plan is
‘sound’.12 Among other factors, the inspector will consider whether the LPA
has adequately assessed the accommodation needs of Gypsies and Travellers
in its area and, if it identified a local need, whether it has allocated a
sufficient number of sites to meet that need.
An inspector can recommend changes to the local plan to make it ‘sound’.13
Because an LPA cannot have a local plan that has not been found ‘sound’, its
choice is between accepting the changes or not having a local plan (in which
case, the ‘presumption in favour of sustainable development’ will apply).14Gypsies and Travellers: Planning provisions in England

1.2 Changes to planning policy
In 2004, the Labour Government introduced section 225 of the Housing Act
2004. It required local housing authorities to assess the accommodation
needs of Gypsies and Travellers who permanently or temporarily resided in
their area. Local authorities had to prepare a strategy setting out how they
intended to meet these needs, as part of their wider housing strategy.15
Section 255 of the Housing Act 2004 worked in conjunction with changes the
Labour Government made to the planning system through the Planning and
Compulsory Purchase Act 2004.16 The Planning and Compulsory Purchase Act
2004 introduced regional planning bodies. Regional planning bodies drew on
the assessments prepared by local housing authorities under the Housing Act
2004 to identify the accommodation needs of Gypsies and Travellers at a
regional level. Regional planning bodies then set pitch targets for individual
LPAs. LPAs had to ensure their local development plans allocated a sufficient
number of sites to meet the pitch targets for their area.17
The Labour Government published guidance on how LPAs should assess the
accommodation needs of Gypsies and Travellers and how they should plan to
meet their needs: Circular 01/06: Planning for Gypsy and Traveller Caravan
Sites (February 2006)18 and Gypsy and Traveller Accommodation Needs
Assessment Guidance (October 2007).19 In May 2008, it also published a Good
Practice Guidance: Designing Gypsy and Traveller Sites (PDF).
The Coalition Government abolished regional planning bodies and strategies
with the Localism Act 2011.20 It also replaced Circular 01/06 with the planning
policy for Traveller sites in 2012 (updated in 2015 and 2023).21
In 2016, following a consultation, the Conservative Government also revoked
section 225 of the Housing Act 2004. The government said the change would
“simplify and streamline the processes for assessing needs [...] for planning
and housing purposes”.22
