2 How are Gypsies and Travellers defined
in planning policy?
Gypsies and Travellers are defined in planning policy as “persons of nomadic
habit of life whatever their race or origin”. The current definition includes
people who have temporarily or permanently stopped travelling for reasons
relating to health, education or old age. 23 Travelling showpeople are defined
separately in planning policy.
2.1 Changes to the definition over time
Gypsies and Travellers have always been defined as “persons of nomadic
habit of life” in planning policy. However, the government’s approach to
Gypsies and Travellers who have given up travelling has changed over the
years:
• From 1994 to 2006, Gypsies and Travellers were defined based on
nomadism.
• From 2006 to 2015, the definition of Gypsies and Travellers in planning
policy included those who had ceased travelling, whether temporarily or
permanently, for reasons of educational or health needs, or old age.24
Following a consultation, the government changed the definition of Gypsies
and Travellers in planning policy in 2015 to exclude those who had stopped
travelling permanently.25 In its response to the consultation, the government
said members of Gypsy and Traveller communities and their representatives
had raised concerns about changing the definition, but most LPAs which had
responded to the consultation had expressed support for the change.26
In the consultation, the government said applications from Gypsies and
Travellers who had stopped travelling permanently should not be treated
differently to applications from other settled populations:
