2.2 Legal challenge to definition
The government’s decision to change the definition of Gypsies and Travellers
in planning policy in 2015 formed the basis of a judicial review. Judicial review
means the decision of a public body, such as a planning decision taken by the
Planning Inspectorate, is challenged in court. The focus of judicial review is on
whether a decision was made in a proper and lawful manner.
Lisa Smith challenged in court the refusal of her application for planning
permission (by the LPA and the Planning Inspectorate on appeal) for a
permanent site for Gypsies and Travellers at Coalville in Leicestershire. Her
representatives argued that the 2015 definition unlawfully discriminated
against elderly and disabled Gypsies and Travellers.
In its June 2021 judgement, the High Court decided that the definition was not
unlawful because the exclusion of permanently settled Gypsies and Travellers
was “objectively and reasonably justified”. The judge ruling on the case said:
the Secretary of State was plainly justified in drawing a distinction between the
specific land-use needs of those seeking to lead a nomadic lifestyle and those
seeking a more settled existence.30
Ms Smith then appealed the decision of the High Court in the Court of Appeal.
The Court of Appeal allowed the appeal. The judges on the case said that “the
