3 Permissions needed for Gypsy and
Traveller sites
To station caravans on land, planning permission from the local planning
authority (LPA) may be needed. If a caravan site is run by a private company
or organisation rather than the local authority, it may also require a site
licence from the local authority.
3.1 Planning permission
Someone wanting to station caravans on land will usually require planning
permission from the LPA because it constitutes ‘development’ under the
planning system. If caravans intended for residential use are stationed on
land that is used for other purposes (such as agricultural land), this may also
constitute a ‘material change of use’ that requires planning permission.37
Exceptions apply if the development or material change of use are covered by
‘permitted development rights’. These provide that planning permission from
the LPA is usually not required, for example, to station up to three caravans
on land that is at least five acres for up to 28 days (in any 12 months).38
For further information about ‘permitted development rights’ and what it
means to ‘materially’ change the use of land, see the Library briefing on
Permitted development and change of use (March 2024).
How do LPAs decide planning applications?
LPAs will decide planning applications in line with their local plan, unless
‘material considerations’ indicate otherwise.39 If LPAs identified a need for
Gypsy and Traveller sites in their area (see section 1.1), their local plan will
usually set out where these sites should be located.
If LPAs receive planning applications for land that is not allocated for Gypsy
and Traveller sites in local plans, or where the LPA has not identified a need
for Gypsy and Traveller sites in its area, the government’s planning policy for
