3 What are material considerations?
Material considerations are reasons why an LPA can decide a planning
application in a way that is not in line with its local plan.40
There is no statutory definition or set list of material considerations. However,
the courts have generally ruled that purely private interests, for example, the
impact on neighbouring property values, cannot be material considerations.41
One material consideration is the National Planning Policy Framework, which
sets out the government’s planning policies, and the government’s planning
policy for Traveller sites is a material consideration for Gypsy and Traveller
sites. A (non-exhaustive) list of other material considerations is set out on the
government’s planning portal.Gypsies and Travellers: Planning provisions in England
An LPA must take the representations that it receives in response to its
consultation into account when making its decision.45 However, an LPA will
not necessarily refuse planning permission if residents object to a planning
application. It may still grant planning permission if its local plan or other
material considerations indicate otherwise.
For further information about how individuals can get involved in the planning
process, see the Library article, Influencing the planning process (England)
(August 2023).
The government’s planning policy for Traveller sites advises LPAs to consider
how they can overcome objections, such as by attaching conditions to
planning permission or negotiating planning obligations. For example, LPAs
could limit the number of days caravans can stay on a site or the number of
caravans that can be stationed on a site at any point in time.46
3.2 Gypsy and Traveller sites on green belt land
The government’s National Planning Framework says that development on
the green belt is generally “inappropriate” and “is, by definition, harmful to
the Green Belt”.49 It provides that LPAs should grant planning permission to
development on the green belt only in “very special circumstances”.50
