4 What if planning permission is refused?
If an LPA refuses planning permission, the applicant can appeal that decision.
Most appeals are decided by the Planning Inspectorate, an executive agency
of the Department for Levelling Up, Housing and Communities (DLUHC).47
The Secretary of State can “recover” an appeal for their own determination,
instead of letting the Planning Inspectorate make a decision on it.48
For further information about challenges to LPA’s decisions, see the Library
briefing on planning appeals (England) (April 2024). For further information
about the Secretary of State’s powers, see the Library briefing on ‘call-in’ of
planning applications (England) (April 2024).Gypsies and Travellers: Planning provisions in England
The government’s planning policy for Traveller sites clarifies that temporary
and permanent Gypsy and Traveller sites on the green belt are considered
“inappropriate development”. It says that personal circumstances and unmet
need are unlikely to constitute “very special circumstances”, although in
decisions affecting children, this is “subject to the best interests of the child”:
Subject to the best interests of the child, personal circumstances and unmet
need are unlikely to clearly outweigh harm to the Green Belt and any other
harm so as to establish very special circumstances.51
An equalities statement supporting the government’s 2015 consultation on its
planning policy for Traveller sites explains the meaning of the term “subject to
the best interest of the child”:
Recent UK case law derived from the United Nations Convention on the Rights
of the Child (UNCRC) establishes that the best interests of the child are a
primary consideration in planning decisions affecting children, and that no
consideration is inherently more important than the best interests of the child.
Substantial weight should therefore continue to be given to the best interests
of the child.52
For further information about (general) green belt planning policy, see the
Library briefing on the green belt (December 2023).
Recovery of appeals related to sites on green belt land
In 2013, the government adopted a policy that the Secretary of State would
consider ‘recovering’ planning appeals (see box 4) related to Gypsy and
Traveller sites. The Secretary of State’s decision to recover two of these
appeals was challenged in 2014 on equalities grounds, and the government
subsequently dropped the policy in 2015. Further information is set out below.
In a written statement in July 2013, the then Under-Secretary of State at the
Department for Communities and Local Government (DCLG), Brandon Lewis,
announced that the Secretary of State would consider ‘recovering’ planning
appeals related to Gypsy and Traveller sites on green belt land. He said the
Secretary of State would not necessarily recover all relevant appeals.53
If an appeal is recovered, the Secretary of State, rather than a planning
inspector, makes the final decision on the appeal.
In January 2014, Brandon Lewis said the Secretary of State would continue to
consider recovering appeals related to Gypsy and Traveller sites on green belt
land. He said the government was concerned whether appeal decisions were
