Legal challenge to recovery of appeals
The Secretary of State’s decision to recover appeals related to Gypsy and
Traveller sites on green belt land formed the basis of a judicial review. Sarah
Coates and Charmaine Moore challenged the Secretary of State’s decision to
recover their appeals in the High Court on equalities grounds. The claimants
had appealed the refusal of planning permission for caravan sites (at Hone in
Kent and in the London Borough of Bromley) with the Planning Inspectorate,
and their appeals had been recovered by the Secretary of State.55
The court found that, although it was not the intention set out in the written
ministerial statements, the Secretary of State recovered 100% of relevant
appeals in September 2013. In September 2014, once they were notified about
possible judicial review proceedings, the Secretary of State recovered 75% of
relevant appeals. This led to a “very substantial” delay in decision-making.56
The judge ruling on the case concluded that, although the written ministerial
statements were not unlawful, “the practice of recovering all appeals, or an
arbitrary percentage thereof, was and is unlawful”.
The judge said the Secretary of State’s decision to recover all or a certain
percentage of appeals breached the Equalities Act 2010, because it had put
Gypsies and Travellers at “a very real disadvantage” (because their appeals
took longer to determine). The judge also said, in the cases of Mrs Moore and
Ms Coates, the Secretary of State also breached the European Convention of
Human Rights. The judge therefore quashed the Secretary of State’s decision
to recover the appeals made by Sarah Coates and Charmaine Moore.57
The judge emphasised that the judgement did not prevent the Secretary of
State from recovering appeals related to Gypsy and Traveller sites, as long as
the Secretary of State’s decisions were based on the individual merits of each
case and “properly considered [...] within the parameters of the 2010 Act”.58
