3.3 Caravan site licence
In addition to planning permission, the people wanting to station caravans on
land may also require a site licence under the Caravan Sites and Control of
Development Act 1960.61 The term “caravan site” is defined as “any land on
which a caravan is stationed for the purposes of human habitation and land
which is used in conjunction with land on which a caravan is stationed”.62
A site licence is not required if conditions set out in Schedule 1 of the 1960 Act
are met, for example, if up three caravans are stationed on land of at least
five acres for a maximum period of 28 days (in any 12 months) or for caravans
by travelling showpeople who are members of an organisation.63 Sites owned
by local authorities also do not require a site licence.
Caravan site licences are issued by local authorities. A local authority can
attach conditions to a site licence (for example, limiting the number of days
caravans can be stationed on a site or the number of caravans allowed on a
site).64
