5 Dealing with unauthorised
developments and encampments
Failure to obtain planning permission where it is required is ‘unauthorised
development’. It can result in enforcement action by the local authority.
Entering and occupying land belonging to private landowners or public
authorities without their permission is an ‘unauthorised encampment’. The
police have powers to take to deal with unauthorised encampments.
5.1 Unauthorised developments
Unauthorised development occurs when land is developed, or there has been
a material change of use of land, but the appropriate planning permission is
not obtained in advance. Failure to obtain planning permission where it is
required is considered a ‘breach in planning control’.70
It is also a planning breach not to comply with the conditions a local planning
authority (LPA) has attached to planning permission (for example, if more
caravans are stationed on land than permitted or they stay on a temporary
site for longer than allowed).
LPAs may allow a ‘retrospective planning application’ where permission has
not been sought and a breach has occurred. LPAs can also take enforcement
action against planning breaches. It is up to LPAs to decide whether they take
enforcement action and what type of action they take.
The government’s National Planning Policy Framework advises LPAs to “act
proportionately” in responding to planning breaches. It also notes, however,
that “effective enforcement is important to maintain public confidence in the
planning system”.71 Its planning policy for Traveller sites advises LPAs to “aim
to reduce the number of unauthorised developments” in their plan-making
and decision-taking.72
An article by the charity Shelter highlights that, when considering whether
they take enforcement action against Gypsy and Traveller sites, LPAs should
