What enforcement powers do LPAs have?
One of the tools at an LPA’s disposal are enforcement notices.74 Enforcement
notices require an individual or developer to take certain steps to remedy a
planning breach, for example to stop certain activities or to remove buildings
or works from land.
It is a criminal offence not to comply with an enforcement notice, with a
penalty on conviction of an unlimited fine.75 If a person who has been served
with an enforcement notice does not comply with the notice, an LPA can also
take steps to remedy the planning breach itself and recover the costs from
the owner or occupier of the land.76
Generally, LPAs must take enforcement action within 10 years of a planning
breach occurring.77 Where a breach has been deliberately concealed, an LPA
could apply to the magistrate’s court for an enforcement order which would
allow it to take enforcement action after that time limit has expired.78
For further information about LPA’s enforcement powers, see government
guidance on enforcement and post-permission matters and a Library briefing
on planning enforcement in England (July 2019).
Appeals against enforcement action
It is possible to appeal the LPA’s refusal of retrospective planning permission
and an enforcement notice.
However, the person who undertook unauthorised development has only one
opportunity to obtain planning permission retrospectively: either by applying
for retrospective planning permission or by appealing an enforcement notice
on the grounds that they should have been granted planning permission.79
