5.2 Failure to obtain a site licence
It is an offence not to obtain a caravan site licence where it is required, with a
penalty on conviction of an unlimited fine.80
It is also an offence not to comply with the conditions that are attached to a
site licence (for example, conditions limiting the number of caravans or the
number of days that caravans can be stationed on a site). On conviction, it is
subject to a fine up to £2,500. If a site owner has been convicted of failing to
comply with site licence conditions at least twice, a local authority can also
apply to the magistrate’s court to revoke their site licence.81
5.3 Unauthorised encampments
Unauthorised encampments occur if trespassers occupy land belonging to
private landowners or public authorities without their permission. The police
have powers to deal with unauthorised encampments.
In 2022, following a consultation, the government lowered the threshold at
which police can use powers in the Police, Crime, Sentencing and Courts Act
2022 to deal with unauthorised encampments.82 The 2022 Act also created
new offence of residing in, or with, a vehicle on land without permission.
What powers do police have to deal with unauthorised
encampments?
Under the Criminal Justice and Public Order Act 1994, as amended by the
Police, Crime, Sentencing and Courts Act 2022, police have the following
powers to deal with unauthorised encampments:
• Under section 60, it is a criminal offence to reside in, or with, a vehicle on
land without consent and to have caused or be likely to cause significant
damage, disruption, destruction, or distress.
• Section 61 gives the police the power to direct people away from land if
they are in an encampment that consists of at least six vehicles, they are
deemed to have caused “damage, disruption or distress”, or their
encampment is on (or partly on) a highway.
